    <p class="articletitle">
        Microsoft SQL Server for Beginners</p>
    <p class="articlesub">
        Series Index</p>
    <p>
        This series is intended for beginning programmers who would like to become 
        familiar with Microsoft SQL Server from a developer perspective. It provides 
        guidance on the installation of SQL Server and integrating a database with a 
        programming solution. A basic level of familiarity with database concepts is a 
        prerequisite.</p>
    <p>
        <a href="../Articles/201208151223.aspx">Part I:&nbsp; From Desktop to Network</a></p>
    <p class="indent">
        This article explores the differences between a desktop database software such 
        as Microsoft Access and Microsoft SQL Server, an enterprise database system. 
        Technical and practical reasons for choosing one over the other are presented.</p>
    <p>
        <a href="../Articles/201208201834.aspx">Part II: Installing SQL Server Express</a></p>
    <p class="indent">
        While SQL Server is intended as a network database, the Express edition enables 
        the average home user to run it on their PC for training, testing and 
        development purposes. This article provides instruction on downloading the 
        correct components and explains the various steps of the installation.</p>
    <p>
        <a href="../Articles/201208271357.aspx">Part III: SQL Server Management Studio</a></p>
    <p class="indent">
        SQL Studio Management Studio (SSMS) is a powerful interface for connecting to 
        local and remote instances of SQL Server and managing databases. This chapter 
        shows how to use SSMS to connect to a SQL Server instance and create a basic 
        database.</p>
    <p>
        <a href="../Articles/201209041141.aspx">Part IV: Installing the AdventureWorks Database</a></p>
    <p class="indent">
        This article provides complete instructions on downloading and installing 
        Microsoft&#39;s AdventureWorks sample database for SQL Server. The article also 
        features an explanation of running commands and scripts within SQL Server 
        Management Studio.</p>
    <p>
        <a href="../Articles/201209131252.aspx">Part V: Using LocalDB</a></p>
    <p class="indent">
        For developers who don&#39;t want to devote the space to a full installation of SQL 
        Server Express and don&#39;t need all the bells and whistles, SQL Server 2012 
        LocalDB is a stripped down alternative that offers most of the features of a SQL 
        Server instance with a much smaller footprint. This chapter shows how to install 
        LocalDB, create multiple instances of SQL Server with it, access those instances 
        through SQL Server Management Studio and install the AdventureWorks sample 
        database.</p>
